You are working in /home/mega/OmegA-Architecture/web/src/. Make the following three changes to upgrade the voice-to-voice pipeline in the OmegA Next.js app.

## Context

- `/api/tts/route.ts` —  2.5 Flash TTS, returns base64 WAV. Already good.
- `/api/stt/route.ts` — OpenAI Whisper endpoint. Accepts multipart/form-data with `audio` file. Returns `{ text: string }`. EXISTS but is NOT used by the voice engine.
- `/api/chat/route.ts` — Provider waterfall (Vercel Gateway → xAI → ). Takes `{ user, history, sessionId }`. Returns SSE stream.
- `hooks/useVoiceEngine.ts` — Uses browser Web Speech API for STT. Already handles TTS playback via `/api/tts`.
- `app/page.tsx` — Main chat UI, uses `useVoiceEngine`.

## Change 1: Add voiceMode to chat route

In `app/api/chat/route.ts`:

1. Accept a new optional `voiceMode: boolean` field in the POST body alongside `user`, `history`, `sessionId`
2. When `voiceMode` is true, append this to the system prompt (AFTER the existing `SYNTHESIS_DIRECTIVE` + memory block):

```
━━━ VOICE MODE ━━━
You are speaking aloud. The user will hear your response via text-to-speech.
Rules:
- Keep responses under 3 sentences unless a longer answer is truly necessary.
- No markdown formatting, no bullet points, no headers — plain spoken sentences only.
- No "certainly", "of course", "absolutely". Just answer directly.
- If you need to think through something complex, say one sentence summary then offer to go deeper.
━━━ END VOICE MODE ━━━
```

The system string construction is at line ~329:
```typescript
const system = `${SYNTHESIS_DIRECTIVE}\n\n━━━ RAW DATA FROM MEMORY SYSTEMS ━━━\n\n${rawContext}\n\n━━━ END RAW DATA ━━━\n${conversationContext}`;
```

Change it to:
```typescript
const voiceDirective = voiceMode ? `\n\n━━━ VOICE MODE ━━━\nYou are speaking aloud. The user will hear your response via text-to-speech.\nRules:\n- Keep responses under 3 sentences unless a longer answer is truly necessary.\n- No markdown formatting, no bullet points, no headers — plain spoken sentences only.\n- No "certainly", "of course", "absolutely". Just answer directly.\n- If you need to think through something complex, say one sentence summary then offer to go deeper.\n━━━ END VOICE MODE ━━━` : '';
const system = `${SYNTHESIS_DIRECTIVE}\n\n━━━ RAW DATA FROM MEMORY SYSTEMS ━━━\n\n${rawContext}\n\n━━━ END RAW DATA ━━━\n${conversationContext}${voiceDirective}`;
```

Also extract `voiceMode` from the request body:
```typescript
const { user, history, sessionId, voiceMode } = (await req.json()) as { user: string; history?: Msg[]; sessionId?: string; voiceMode?: boolean };
```

## Change 2: Upgrade useVoiceEngine to use Whisper

In `hooks/useVoiceEngine.ts`, add a `useWhisper?: boolean` option to `VoiceEngineOptions` (default `false`).

When `useWhisper` is true:
- Instead of using browser SpeechRecognition to produce a transcript, use `MediaRecorder` to capture audio
- When the user stops speaking (silence detection), stop the MediaRecorder, collect the blob, POST it to `/api/stt` as multipart/form-data with field name `audio` and filename `recording.webm`
- Use the returned `{ text }` as the transcript, then call `onTranscript(text)`
- During recording show interim state as 'listening', during the fetch show 'thinking'

Implement this as a parallel code path inside `useVoiceEngine`. When `useWhisper` is false, behavior is exactly as before (Web Speech API). When `useWhisper` is true, use MediaRecorder.

Add silence detection for Whisper mode: start a 1.5s silence timer based on AudioContext analyser level dropping below 0.05. When silence timer fires, stop recording and send to Whisper.

Here is the Whisper recording approach to add:

```typescript
// Whisper recording refs (only used when useWhisper=true)
const mediaRecorderRef = useRef<MediaRecorder | null>(null);
const audioChunksRef = useRef<Blob[]>([]);
const silenceTimerRef = useRef<ReturnType<typeof setTimeout> | null>(null);

const startWhisperRecording = useCallback(async () => {
  try {
    const stream = await navigator.mediaDevices.getUserMedia({ audio: true });
    micStreamRef.current = stream;
    const recorder = new MediaRecorder(stream, { mimeType: 'audio/webm' });
    audioChunksRef.current = [];
    mediaRecorderRef.current = recorder;

    recorder.ondataavailable = (e) => {
      if (e.data.size > 0) audioChunksRef.current.push(e.data);
    };

    recorder.onstop = async () => {
      const blob = new Blob(audioChunksRef.current, { type: 'audio/webm' });
      audioChunksRef.current = [];
      if (blob.size < 1000) { setState('listening'); startWhisperRecording(); return; }

      setState('thinking');
      const form = new FormData();
      form.append('audio', blob, 'recording.webm');
      try {
        const res = await fetch('/api/stt', { method: 'POST', body: form });
        const data = await res.json();
        if (data.text?.trim()) {
          onTranscript(data.text.trim());
        } else {
          setState('listening');
          startWhisperRecording();
        }
      } catch {
        setState('listening');
        startWhisperRecording();
      }
    };

    recorder.start(100); // collect chunks every 100ms

    // Silence detection via analyser
    const ctx = getAudioCtx();
    const src = ctx.createMediaStreamSource(stream);
    const analyser = ctx.createAnalyser();
    analyser.fftSize = 128;
    src.connect(analyser);
    analyserRef.current = analyser;
    startLevelTick(analyser, setMicLevel, micAnimRef);

    const buf = new Uint8Array(analyser.frequencyBinCount);
    const checkSilence = () => {
      analyser.getByteFrequencyData(buf);
      const avg = buf.reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0) / buf.length;
      if (avg < 5) {
        if (!silenceTimerRef.current) {
          silenceTimerRef.current = setTimeout(() => {
            silenceTimerRef.current = null;
            if (mediaRecorderRef.current?.state === 'recording') {
              stopMicAnalyzer();
              mediaRecorderRef.current.stop();
            }
          }, 1500);
        }
      } else {
        if (silenceTimerRef.current) {
          clearTimeout(silenceTimerRef.current);
          silenceTimerRef.current = null;
        }
      }
      if (stateRef.current === 'listening') requestAnimationFrame(checkSilence);
    };
    requestAnimationFrame(checkSilence);
  } catch (e) {
    console.warn('[VoiceEngine] Whisper recording failed:', e);
  }
}, [getAudioCtx, onTranscript, setState, stopMicAnalyzer]);
```

Add this to the `toggle` function: when `useWhisper` is true and toggling on, call `startWhisperRecording()` instead of `wakeUp(); startRecognition()`.

When toggling off in Whisper mode, stop the MediaRecorder and clear silence timer.

## Change 3: Wire voiceMode through page.tsx

In `app/page.tsx`:

1. Add a `voiceMode` state: `const [voiceMode, setVoiceMode] = useState(true)` — default ON since this is a voice-first app

2. Pass `voiceMode: true` in the `chatStream` call when `voiceMode` is true. The `chatStream` function is in `lib/api.ts` — check its signature first and add `voiceMode` parameter if needed.

3. Pass `useWhisper: true` to `useVoiceEngine` (the voice engine options).

4. In the bottom actions bar, add a small toggle button next to the existing Type/Mic buttons that switches between voice mode and text mode, showing current state. Something like:
```tsx
<button 
  className={s.typeBtn} 
  onClick={() => setVoiceMode(v => !v)}
  title={voiceMode ? "Voice mode on" : "Voice mode off"}
  style={{ opacity: voiceMode ? 1 : 0.5 }}
>
  {voiceMode ? '🎙 Voice' : '💬 Text'}
</button>
```

## Also check lib/api.ts

Read `lib/api.ts` first. The `chatStream` function probably needs a `voiceMode` parameter added to pass it to the POST body. Add it if needed.

---

## Important constraints
- Do not break any existing functionality
- The Web Speech API path must still work when `useWhisper` is false  
- TypeScript must compile (no type errors, use proper types)
- Keep the existing wake word system intact — it should still work in non-Whisper mode
- Read each file before editing it

